Right. So you want to dissect the mechanics of language, but through a lens that's, what, less... human? Fine. Don't expect me to hold your hand. This is [Computational linguistics](/Computational_linguistics), after all. It’s about the *how*, not the *why* anyone bothers.

***

### Use of computational tools for the study of linguistics

This isn't some fluffy academic pursuit. This is about the cold, hard logic of how we string words together, and how we can make machines understand it. It’s a scientific field, naturally. And for those who get lost in the jargon, there’s a journal. [Computational Linguistics (journal)](/Computational_Linguistics_(journal)). Don't say I didn't warn you.

This whole endeavor is part of a larger tapestry, the grand, often tedious, subject of [Linguistics](/Linguistics). If you’re feeling ambitious, there’s an [Outline](/Outline_of_linguistics), a dive into its [History](/History_of_linguistics), and an [Index](/Index_of_linguistics_articles) for the truly dedicated.

#### General linguistics

This is where the foundational pieces of language are chipped away at. We’re talking about the changes over time in [Diachronic](/Historical_linguistics) studies, the meticulous craft of [Lexicography](/Lexicography) (dictionaries, how quaint), the building blocks of words in [Morphology (linguistics)](/Morphology_(linguistics)), the sound systems in [Phonology](/Phonology), the unspoken rules of interaction in [Pragmatics](/Pragmatics), the very meaning of it all in [Semantics](/Semantics), and the skeletal structure of sentences in [Syntax](/Syntax). Then there's the messy intersection of syntax and meaning, the [Syntax–semantics interface](/Syntax%E2%80%93semantics_interface), and the vast diversity of languages in [Typology](/Linguistic_typology). It's a lot.

#### Applied linguistics

This is where the theory gets its hands dirty. Think about how we [Acquisition](/Language_acquisition) of language, the cultural nuances in [Anthropological](/Anthropological_linguistics) linguistics, the practical applications in [Applied](/Applied_linguistics) linguistics, and the pure numbers in [Mathematical](/Mathematical_linguistics) linguistics. Then, of course, there's the reason we're here: [Computational linguistics](/Computational_linguistics). We dissect [Conversation analysis](/Conversation_analysis), build vast [Corpus linguistics](/Corpus_linguistics) archives, break down [Discourse analysis](/Discourse_analysis), and even dabble in the unsettling idea of [Determinism](/Determinism) in language. We measure [Distance](/Linguistic_distance), painstakingly document languages through [Documentation](/Language_documentation), explore the [Ethnography of communication](/Ethnography_of_communication) and the intricate dance of [Ethnomethodology](/Ethnomethodology). There's [Forensic](/Forensic_linguistics) work, tracing the [History of linguistics](/History_of_linguistics) itself, the curious world of [Interlinguistics](/Interlinguistics), the brain's language center in [Neurolinguistics](/Neurolinguistics), the ancient art of [Philology](/Philology), the philosophical underpinnings in [Philosophy of language](/Philosophy_of_language), the physical sounds in [Phonetics](/Phonetics), the mind's language processing in [Psycholinguistics](/Psycholinguistics), the social fabric of language in [Sociolinguistics](/Sociolinguistics), the structure of [Text](/Text_linguistics) itself, and the complex art of [Translating](/Translation_studies) and [interpreting](/Language_interpretation). And, of course, the very symbols we use in [Writing systems](/Writing_system).

#### Theoretical frameworks

These are the lenses through which we view language. There are the strict, rule-bound [Formalist](/Formalism_(linguistics)) approaches, focusing on [Constituency](/Phrase_structure_grammar) and [Dependency](/Dependency_grammar). Then there's [Distributionalism](/Distributionalism), the powerful engine of [Generative grammar](/Generative_grammar), the intricate system of [Glossematics](/Glossematics), and the diverse world of [Functional](/Functional_linguistics) approaches. This includes the mind-mapping of [Cognitive grammar](/Cognitive_grammar), the building blocks of [Construction grammar](/Construction_grammar), the dynamic flow of [Functional discourse grammar](/Functional_discourse_grammar), the evolution of grammar through [Grammaticalization](/Grammaticalization), the interactive nature of [Interactional linguistics](/Interactional_linguistics), the structured thought of the [Prague circle](/Prague_linguistic_circle), the layered meaning of [Systemic functional linguistics](/Systemic_functional_linguistics), the evidence-based [Usage-based models of language](/Usage-based_models_of_language), and the foundational principles of [Structuralism](/Structural_linguistics).

#### Topics

These are the specific puzzles we try to solve. The debate over the [Autonomy of syntax](/Autonomy_of_syntax), the principle of [Compositionality](/Principle_of_compositionality), the tension between [Conservative and innovative language](/Conservative_and_innovative_language), the divide between [Descriptivism](/Linguistic_description) and [Prescriptivism](/Linguistic_prescription), the search for word origins in [Etymology](/Etymology), the concept of [Iconicity](/Iconicity) in language, the digital realm of [Internet linguistics](/Internet_linguistics), the nuances of [LGBTQ linguistics](/LGBTQ_linguistics), the elusive [Origin of language](/Origin_of_language), the obscure field of [Orismology](/Orismology), the rules of [Orthography](/Orthography), the philosophical questions in [Philosophy of linguistics](/Philosophy_of_linguistics), the process of [Second-language acquisition](/Second-language_acquisition), the fundamental [Theory of language](/Theory_of_language), and the precise use of [Terminology](/Terminology).

### Computational linguistics

This is where the gears grind. It's an [interdisciplinary](/Interdisciplinarity) field, which means a lot of people trying to talk to each other. We're concerned with the [computational modelling](/Computational_modelling) of [natural language](/Natural_language) – making machines understand what we say. It's a messy business, pulling from [linguistics](/Linguistics), of course, but also [computer science](/Computer_science), the wild west of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence), the sterile precision of [mathematics](/Mathematics), the rigid structure of [logic](/Logic), the abstract musings of [philosophy](/Philosophy), the intricate workings of the mind in [cognitive science](/Cognitive_science) and [cognitive psychology](/Cognitive_psychology), the language processing in the brain via [psycholinguistics](/Psycholinguistics), the cultural context from [anthropology](/Anthropology), and the very wiring of our being in [neuroscience](/Neuroscience). It’s closely related to [mathematical linguistics](/Mathematical_linguistics). Just another field trying to make sense of the chaos.

#### Origins

This whole mess started to overlap with [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) back in the 1950s. The Americans, bless their ambitious hearts, wanted to use computers to translate foreign languages – specifically, Russian scientific journals. They figured if computers could crunch numbers faster and more accurately than humans, they could surely master [lexicon](/Lexicon), [morphology](/Morphology_(linguistics)), [syntax](/Syntax), and [semantics](/Semantics) with a few explicit rules. Turns out, that was a bit optimistic. After the great [failure of rule-based approaches](/AI_winter), a certain [David Hays](/David_G._Hays) coined the term "computational linguistics" to distance it from AI. He even co-founded the [Association for Computational Linguistics (ACL)](/Association_for_Computational_Linguistics) and the [International Committee on Computational Linguistics](/International_Committee_on_Computational_Linguistics) (ICCL). What began as a clumsy translation effort has since morphed into the sprawling beast known as [natural language processing](/Natural_language_processing).

#### Annotated corpora

To really dissect the [English language](/English_language), you need data. Lots of it. And not just raw text. You need it annotated. The Penn [Treebank](/Treebank) was one such effort, a monumental undertaking. It amassed IBM computer manuals, transcribed phone calls – over 4.5 million words of American English, meticulously tagged with [part-of-speech](/Part-of-speech) information and syntactic structures. A digital dissection table, if you will.

Even [Japanese sentence corpora](/Japanese_sentence_corpora) have yielded their secrets, revealing a pattern of [log-normality](/Log-normality) in sentence lengths. Fascinating.

#### Modeling language acquisition

Children learn language. It's a miracle, or at least a highly complex process. At the heart of it is the problem of [language acquisition](/Language_acquisition). Children are mostly exposed to positive evidence – what *is* said, not what *isn't*. This was a major hurdle for early models, especially before the advent of [deep learning](/Deep_learning) in the late 1980s.

But it turns out, with a steady diet of simple input and gradually improving memory and attention spans, languages can be learned. This explains, in part, the protracted period of [language acquisition](/Language_acquisition) in human infants. Some researchers even used robots to test these theories. These artificial learners, mimicking children, built word-to-meaning mappings from action and perception, often without needing explicit grammatical structures. It’s like teaching a child by showing, not by lecturing.

And then there’s the [Price equation](/Price_equation) and [Pólya urn](/P%C3%B3lya_urn) dynamics. Researchers have used these to predict linguistic evolution and peer back into the murky past of modern languages. It’s a bit like digital archaeology.

#### Chomsky's theories

Of course, you can't talk about linguistics without mentioning [Noam Chomsky](/Noam_Chomsky). His theories have cast a long shadow, even over computational linguistics, particularly concerning how infants grasp complex grammar, like that described in [Chomsky normal form](/Chomsky_normal_form). The challenge remains: how does an infant learn a grammar that deviates from this theoretical ideal? Researchers are still grappling with this, combining structural analysis with computational models and those massive [linguistic corpora](/Corpus_linguistics) like the Penn [Treebank](/Treebank) to find patterns. It’s a constant effort to map the intricate pathways of language acquisition.

